Imagine a long webpage with many sections (like a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific part of it (for example, page.html#section7), can the Web server first transmit that part and then transmit the rest?
Stream order:
1. HTML document from the beginning until the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for section 7
3. The HTML code for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser should ensure that parts 1 to 6 are inserted above the 7th part on the web page.
Is this reasonable? Is it useful?
My goal is to make the linked part (#section7) render as quickly as possible without having to reimplement it with JavaScript or something similar. I want a very long HTML document where the linked part still renders quickly. It can be achieved purely with HTML.
The content can be streamed like this, and then the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
等等
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in the correct order.
@user22 In fact, you can achieve reordering of document content without using JS. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the URL hash part; instead, you need to use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to see first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use templates with slots
@user23 Correct. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) and the DOM order are not aligned. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming and the browser could arrange the content in order in the DOM, that would be quite useful.
However, the slot approach seems promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to automatically fix the DOM order?
@user23 Exactly, that's what I'm thinking. The sole reason for streaming the 7th part first is to allow the user to see it as quickly as possible. If we could achieve this without changing the DOM order, that would be ideal, ensuring that the final DOM and visual order are the same as if all parts were streamed in order.
In other words, stream the 7th part first, but the final result (DOM and visual effects) should be exactly the same as if all parts were streamed in order.
@user22 @user33 Can take a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
